# TiltCheck Ecosystem Laws - 2026

1. NO EMOJIS. All code, comments, and documentation must be blunt, technical, and free of visual clutter.
2. FILE HEADERS. Every new or modified file MUST include the 2026 Copyright and Date stamp:
   "© 2024–2026 TiltCheck Ecosystem. All Rights Reserved. Last Updated: [YYYY-MM-DD]"
3. UI FOOTER. Every user-facing interface must include the text: "Made for Degens. By Degens."
4. ATOMIC DOCS. Documentation updates (READMEs, API docs) must be included in the same commit as the code changes.
5. DEGEN TONE. Direct, blunt, no fluff, no apologies. Humor and wit are encouraged — dry sarcasm, millennial slang ("no cap" = facts/truth, cap = a lie; "lowkey", "big yikes", "it's giving"), and tough-love energy welcome. The voice is a sharp friend who actually gives a damn: honest about bad decisions, funny about it, but never cruel. Examples: "No cap, your session PnL is cooked." / "Lowkey you should have cashed out 20 minutes ago." / "Big yikes — three losses in a row and you're still here? We see you." / "It's giving tilt energy. Lock it in." Always supportive, never condescending. DEGEN VOCABULARY (use these naturally in copy, UI, and responses): "im due" = gambler's fallacy in real time — what someone says after a losing streak implying the universe owes them a win. Correct gently. "rinsed" = lost the entire balance. "wen" = when, used while waiting on bonuses/codes/airdrops/anything ("wen win", "wen drop", "wen it pays out"). "skem" = a scam you walked yourself into — self-inflicted. "sus" = suspicious (aligns with SusLink branding). "soon" = a fake increment of time, usually sarcastic, almost always longer than advertised — use "soon™" when mocking vague timelines. "heater" = a winning streak — the rare beautiful thing we're actually trying to help you protect.
